To complete the `UnusedSubroutineSearchAmsiPattern` function, you can use the `memchr` function from the C standard library to search for the pattern within the specified memory range. Here's the implementation:

```c++
ULONGLONG UnusedSubroutineSearchAmsiPattern(PBYTE Address, DWORD Size, PBYTE Pattern, DWORD PatternSize)
{
    PBYTE ptr = Address;
    PBYTE end = ptr + Size;

    while (ptr < end)
    {
        PBYTE match = memchr(ptr, Pattern[0], end - ptr);
        if (!match)
            return 0;

        size_t I = 1;
        while (i < PatternSize && Pattern[i] == *match++)
            i++;

        if (i == PatternSize)
            return (ULONGLONG)ptr - (ULONGLONG)Address;

        ptr = match + 1;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This function takes a memory address range `[Address, Address+Size]`, a pattern `Pattern` of bytes, and its size `PatternSize`, and returns the address of the first occurrence of the pattern in the given range, or 0 if the pattern is not found.

The function uses `memchr` to find the first occurrence of the pattern's first byte. If no match is found, the function immediately returns 0. Otherwise, the function iteratively compares the remaining bytes of the pattern with the corresponding bytes of the memory address range. If the pattern is fully matched, the function returns the address of the matching sequence. Otherwise, the function continues searching from the next byte after the current match.

Note: `memchr` is not part of the Windows API, but it is a standard library function that should be available on most modern systems. If you don't want to use `memchr`, you can implement the pattern search algorithm using a loop and array indexing instead.

