char *getLine(FILE *f) {
    char *buffer = (char *) malloc(1024);
    int i = 0;
    char c = fgetc(f);
    while (c!= '\n' &&!feof(f)) {
        buffer[i++] = c;
        c = fgetc(f);
    }
    buffer[i] = '\0';
    return buffer;
}
```

The function reads a line of text from the file pointed to by `f` using `fgetc` and stores it in a dynamically allocated buffer. It returns the buffer containing the line. Note that `feof` is used to check if we have reached the end of the file, while `fgetc` is used to read characters from the file one by one until we find a newline character or the end of the file. The buffer is null-terminated to make it a proper C string.

