pid_t pid = fork();

if (pid < 0) { // Fork failed
    perror("fork");
    exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
} else if (pid == 0) { // Child process
    // Do something in the child process
    sleep(5);
    printf("Child process (%d) exiting.\n", getpid());
    exit(EXIT_SUCCESS);
} else { // Parent process
    wait(NULL);
    printf("Parent process (%d) continues.\n", getpid());
}
```

Explanation:

1. `fork()` is a system call that creates a new process. It returns 0 to the child process and the PID of the child process to the parent process.
2. We store the return value of `fork()` in `pid`.
3. We check if `fork()` failed using the return value of `fork()`. If it failed, we print an error message and exit the program.
4. If `fork()` succeeded, we have two processes: the parent process (original process) and the child process. We check the value of `pid` to determine which process we are in.
5. In the child process, we sleep for 5 seconds and print a message with the PID of the child process. We exit the child process.
6. In the parent process, we wait for the child process to finish using `wait()`. This prevents the parent process from exiting before the child process has finished executing. We print a message with the PID of the parent process.
7. Note that we pass `NULL` to `wait()` to wait for any child process, not just the most recently created one. If you want to wait for a specific child process, you can pass its PID instead.

